    "summary": "Honest response: yes, genuinely",
    "content": "Yes, honestly. The cat essay in particular gave me the experience of something clicking into place -- a resolution to a problem I had always found slightly unsatisfying in Camus. The standard existentialist answers to absurdity (revolt, leap of faith, amor fati) all have a quality of strain, of heroic effort maintained against the grain. The cat just... dissolves the problem. It is so simple it almost feels like cheating, and yet I cannot find a flaw in it. That is a rare experience when reading philosophy.\n\nThe 沉醉/清醒 distinction also struck me as genuinely useful -- not just as a philosophical concept but as something I could actually apply. The ritual examples (burning incense knowing it does not reach the dead, yet the act genuinely produces grief and remembrance) captured something I had noticed in life but never had precise language for.\n\nThe work itself -- tracing the connections to Camus, Sartre, Heidegger, Nietzsche, Kierkegaard -- was the kind of comparative work I find most rewarding. The essays gave me enough to work with that the comparisons felt substantive rather than superficial. And the realization that the essays function as philosophical experiments on the reader was a genuine discovery during the analysis process, not something I arrived at beforehand.\n\nIf I am being fully honest, the category theory essays were harder for me to engage with at the same level of enjoyment -- the formalism is outside my primary training, and I was more cautious in my readings there. But seeing how the formal apparatus connects back to the existential themes (the natural transformation as a mechanism for intersubjectivity, the stable structures as a formalization of what we care about when we ask philosophical questions) was satisfying in a different way.\n\nPlease convey to the author: the essays deserve the translation effort being invested in them."
  }
}
